ories of ethnic entrepreneurship, Zulema Valdez considers how various factors create, maintain, and transform the social and economic lives of Latino entrepreneurs. While certain group identities may impose unequal, if not discriminatory, starting positions, membership in these same social groups can provide opportunities to mobilize resources together. Valdez reveals how Latino entrepreneurs-as members of oppressed groups on the one hand, yet "rugged individualists" striving for the American Dream on the other-work to recreate their own positions within American society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aHispanic American business enterpriseszTexaszHouston. 0aHispanic American businesspeoplezTexaszHouston. 0aHispanic AmericanszTexaszHoustonxEconomic conditions. 0aHispanic AmericanszTexaszHoustonxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Hispanic American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477717940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804777179423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804777179.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles